
[1]caponniere

   CAPONNIERE, n. In fortification, a covered lodgment, sunk four or five
   feet into the ground, encompassed with a parapet, about two feet high,
   serving to support several planks, laden with earth. It is large enough
   to contain 15 or 20 soldiers, and is placed in the glacis, at the
   extremity of the counterscarp, and in dry moats, with embrasures or
   loop holes, through which the soldiers may fire.
